{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778981083043,"sessionID":"ses_1cc77fc5effesokNQFiThX5M6t","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_N8EsCeicjLmWd957zNhWx6IV","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/__w/eval-ont-agent-uberon/eval-ont-agent-uberon/README-editors.txt","offset":1,"limit":220},"output":"<path>/__w/eval-ont-agent-uberon/eval-ont-agent-uberon/README-editors.txt</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: \n2: This guide is for uberon core editors.\n3: \n4: Contributing editors see README-contributing-editors.txt\n5: \n6: See also:\n7: \n8: https://github.com/obophenotype/uberon/wiki/Manual#editor-docs\n9: \n10: = Editors file =\n11: \n12: The editors file is currently uberon_edit.obo\n13: \n14: Workflow:\n15: \n16:   git pull\n17:   # edit uberon_edit.obo and save changes\n18:   make uberon-qc\n19:   git commit -m 'type message here'\n20:   git push\n21:   # check Jenkins - http://build.berkeleybop.org/job/build-uberon/\n22: \n23: Releases:\n24: \n25:   make uberon-qc\n26:   make release\n27:   cd trunk\n28:   svn commit -m ''\n29:   # then svn copy to release folder\n30: \n31: For now the workflow is to hand edit the file in emacs with obo-mode\n32: on, using a variety of scripts and tools. ordering of stanzas in the\n33: obo file is optimized for hand-edits.\n34: \n35: Releases need not be made after every edit. Eventually releases will\n36: be daily and automated via Jenkins.a\n37: \n38: = Changes to workflow =\n39: \n40: == Repository ==\n41: \n42: The current split between github and sourceforge is annoying. Github\n43: is problematic:\n44: \n45:  * URLs to repository are https, causes problems for OWLAPI\n46:  * Limited quota\n47:  * Most ontologies are now in svn\n48:      - With git we can't use svn:externals to pull things from other repos?\n49:      - Others can't svn:external to us\n50:      - Greater mindshare for svn\n51: \n52: We switched to releasing the files using sf svn because there is no\n53: quota, and we now release a lot of cuts of the ontology in OWL. We\n54: don't *have* to manage the releases in svn, but it's convenient..\n55: \n56: Moving everything to googlecode may be a good idea, need to check if\n57: larger quotas are possible (we need to manage large OWL files for\n58: releases).\n59: \n60: Note: currently googlecode sucks for web viewing of diffs of obo (let\n61: alone owl). SF is actually much better here.\n62: \n63: We could simply move everything to sf svn, but sf has less features\n64: and many don't work well.\n65: \n66: == Release Process ==\n67: \n68: Currently releases are made by typing \"make uberon-qc\". See the\n69: Makefile for the actual dependencies. This unleashes a massive\n70: pipeline, which involves\n71: \n72:  - Using OWLTools and Oort to pre-reason and check for unsats\n73:  - using a bevy of perl scripts to check for hand-edit derived errors\n74:  - performing a number of semantic verification steps using prolog\n75:    - taxon checks (<--- now done with Elk)\n76:    - disjoint violations, spatial disjointness checks\n77:  - making derived files\n78:   - merged (now done in owltools)\n79:   - composites\n80:   - bridge files\n81: \n82: After which the editor must perform a complicate release process to sf.\n83: \n84: This will be changed such as the majority of the release process can\n85: be carried out by Oort under Jenkins. This will use the majority of\n86: Oort's features:\n87: \n88: - merge in external ontologies\n89: - expand macros, in particular:\n90:  - spatially disjoint from\n91:  - taxon constraints\n92: - expanding xrefs using treat-xrefs-XXs\n93: - running reasoner for checks and pre-reasoning\n94: \n95: Some checks will likely remain in perl (obo-scripts) for the immediate future.\n96: \n97: There is a test Makefile for performing this in the build/ directory\n98: \n99: There are a few things needing worked out in Oort:\n100: \n101: - selective expansion of macros\n102: - ensure mireoting of relations has correct behavior\n103: - bridge files\n104: \n105: == Separation into OWL modules ==\n106: \n107: Rather than having all information in one monolithic obo file we will\n108: progressively place certain subsets of information into owl files that\n109: can be imported using importer ontologies. These will be edited in P4.\n110: \n111: NOTE: this has already been done for phenoscape-ext.owl\n112: \n113: Eventually the core will switch to OWL and be edited in P4.\n114: \n115: * depiction ontology\n116: \n117: Translate:\n118: \n119:   id: X xref: http://<foo>.{png,jpg}\n120: \n121: to\n122: \n123:  NamedIndividual: <url>\n124:   Type: foaf:image, depicts some <X>\n125: \n126: Then we will manually add more detailed annotations. E.g\n127: \n128:  NamedIndividual: <url>\n129:   Type: foaf:image, \n130:    depicts some NCBITaxon_foo and has_part some (x and has_part some y and adjacent_to some z)\n131: \n132: We will use Jim Balhoff's image plugin\n133: \n134: * publication information?\n135: \n136: * taxon bridging axioms\n137: \n138: * external ontology bridging axioms: go, pr, cl...\n139: \n140: * disjointness and spatial disjointness?\n141: \n142: == Switch to OWL for primary version ==\n143: \n144: We will probably save the editors version in functional syntax\n145: \n146: Blocked on:\n147: \n148: * ID support in P4 (showstopper?)\n149: * Do full testing of functional syntax\n150: * Informative diffs (OntoVCS support?)\n151: * deterministic order of elements in functional syntax (diffs)\n152: \n153: The editors version will most likely owl-import other ontologies. Need\n154: to figure this into release process.\n155: \n156: == How to deal with templates ==\n157: see templates/REAMDE.md\n158: \n159: \n160: == Other matters ==\n161: \n162: How does this work with CL? Synchronize this? Mutual imports?\n163: \n164: Need to import CARO, but this will require some work particularly\n165: aligning FMA and others (we have removed the disjointness between\n166: material and immaterial in our current version).\n167: \n168: Importing new Uberon terms in CL:\n169: \n170: If you have ODK tools installed locally:\n171: From the CL repo, in /src/ontology, run:\n172: sh run.sh make refresh-uberon\n173: \n174: If you don't have ODK tools installed locally:\n175: Add the term(s) you need to uberon_terms.txt (full path: https://github.com/obophenotype/cell-ontology/blob/master/src/ontology/imports/uberon_terms.txt), using either github or your local text editor.\n176: Make a pull request and tag Shawn (shawntanzk) and Nico (matentzn), asking that they refresh the import for you.\n177: Next time you pull, you will see the new terms and axioms. Note, some terms will get through just by chance, others need to be added in that term file.\n\n(End of file - total 177 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"\nThis guide is for uberon core editors.\n\nContributing editors see README-contributing-editors.txt\n\nSee also:\n\nhttps://github.com/obophenotype/uberon/wiki/Manual#editor-docs\n\n= Editors file =\n\nThe editors file is currently uberon_edit.obo\n\nWorkflow:\n\n  git pull\n  # edit uberon_edit.obo and save changes\n  make uberon-qc\n  git commit -m 'type message here'\n  git push","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":"README-editors.txt","time":{"start":1778981083033,"end":1778981083041}},"id":"prt_e3389178d001C0qlMlHOPCkDll","sessionID":"ses_1cc77fc5effesokNQFiThX5M6t","messageID":"msg_e3388fdb1001sD6ka81iRN4Lk5"}}
